## {{ rule.title }}

[26 U.S.C. § 61(a)(2)](https://uscode.house.gov/view.xhtml?req=granuleid:USC-prelim-title26-section61&num=0&edition=prelim) includes gross income derived from a trade or business, and [26 U.S.C. § 162(a)](https://uscode.house.gov/view.xhtml?req=granuleid:USC-prelim-title26-section162&num=0&edition=prelim) allows a deduction for the ordinary and necessary expenses of carrying on that business. Your [Schedule C (Form 1040)](https://www.irs.gov/forms-pubs/about-schedule-c-form-1040) net profit is the difference between the two.

{# IRS-VERIFIED 2026-06-13 — 2025 Schedule C (Form 1040) line 7 (gross income), line 28 (total expenses), line 31 (net profit = line 7 − line 28), and the on-form instruction "enter on Schedule 1 (Form 1040), line 3, and on Schedule SE, line 2", all against https://www.irs.gov/pub/irs-pdf/f1040sc.pdf #}
{% set sc = rule.outputs[0].value | from_json -%}
{% if sc.declared -%}
The Schedule C netting is:

- Gross receipts / business income ([Schedule C](https://www.irs.gov/forms-pubs/about-schedule-c-form-1040) line 7, § 61(a)(2)): **{{ sc.gross_receipts_usd | money(currency="USD") }}**
- Total business expenses ([Schedule C](https://www.irs.gov/forms-pubs/about-schedule-c-form-1040) line 28, § 162(a) ordinary & necessary): **{{ sc.business_expenses_usd | money(currency="USD") }}**
- **Net profit ([Schedule C](https://www.irs.gov/forms-pubs/about-schedule-c-form-1040) line 31): {{ sc.net_profit_usd | money(currency="USD") }}**

{# IRS-VERIFIED 2026-06-13 — Schedule C line 31 net profit "enter on Schedule 1 (Form 1040), line 3, and on Schedule SE, line 2" per the official 2025 Schedule C PDF https://www.irs.gov/pub/irs-pdf/f1040sc.pdf #}
This single net-profit figure does two jobs and is **not** double-counted: it is **income** — it flows to [Schedule 1 (Form 1040)](https://www.irs.gov/forms-pubs/about-schedule-1-form-1040) line 3 and into your AGI at US25-07 — and it is the **self-employment-tax base** under [§ 1402(a)(12)](https://uscode.house.gov/view.xhtml?req=granuleid:USC-prelim-title26-section1402&num=0&edition=prelim) (× 92.35 %) at US25-SE-TAX. The income is counted once; the self-employment tax is a separate tax on the same earnings, and one-half of that tax is itself deductible from AGI under § 164(f).

The business income is classified **{{ sc.business_income_source }}** for [§ 199A](https://uscode.house.gov/view.xhtml?req=granuleid:USC-prelim-title26-section199A&num=0&edition=prelim) purposes — see the § 199A gate at US25-08A.
{% else -%}
{# IRS-VERIFIED 2026-06-13 — Schedule 1 (Form 1040) line 3 (business income from Schedule C) per https://www.irs.gov/pub/irs-pdf/f1040sc.pdf #}
No Schedule C business income is declared for this return (the taxpayer is a wage earner), so the Schedule C net profit is **{{ sc.net_profit_usd | money(currency="USD") }}** and nothing flows to Schedule 1 line 3 or the self-employment-tax base from this stage.
{% endif %}

